---
import DocPage from '../../../components/DocPage.astro'; import CodeBlock from '../../../components/CodeBlock.astro'; import Callout from '../../../components/Callout.astro';
const gd = `extends Control

const GuaAutoAdapterScript := preload(
  "res://addons/gua/gua_auto_adapter.gd"
)

var ui := GuaAutoAdapterScript.new()

func _ready() -> void:
  ui.attach(self)
  ui.update("title")
  ui.start_inspector_bridge(8765)

func _process(_delta: float) -> void:
  ui.update("title")`;
---
<DocPage eyebrow="GODOT / UI IMPLEMENTATION" title="Implementing UI" lead="You do not rewrite your UI for Gua. Build it from standard Controls, then give the root Control to the automatic collector." description="Add the Gua GDScript adapter to a Godot UI." section="godot">
  <Callout kind="tip" title="Install from the latest release"><p>Open the <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/releases/latest">latest Gua release</a> and download <code>gua-godot-plugin-windows-debug-v*.zip</code>. Extract it and copy <code>addons/gua</code> into your Godot project's <code>addons/</code> directory. This packaged add-on is the normal installation path.</p></Callout>
  <h2>Install the packaged add-on</h2><ol class="steps"><li><strong>Open the latest release</strong><p>Download the Godot ZIP from the release assets and extract it.</p></li><li><strong>Copy addons/gua</strong><CodeBlock title="Expected layout" lang="text" code={`your-game/\n├─ project.godot\n└─ addons/\n   └─ gua/\n      ├─ gua.gdextension\n      ├─ gua_auto_adapter.gd\n      ├─ plugin.cfg\n      └─ bin/`} /></li><li><strong>Open the project in Godot</strong><p>Check the Godot output to confirm that the GDExtension loaded successfully.</p></li></ol>
  <h2>Attach it from GDScript</h2><ol class="steps"><li><strong>Preload the adapter explicitly</strong><p>Explicit preload avoids depending on <code>class_name</code> registration order.</p><CodeBlock title="main.gd" lang="gdscript" code={gd} /></li><li><strong>Pin IDs only where stability matters</strong><p>The default ID comes from the NodePath. Use metadata when an ID must survive scene-tree refactoring.</p><CodeBlock title="Stable and sensitive fields" lang="gdscript" code={`name_input.set_meta("gua_id", "login-user")\npassword_input.set_meta("gua_id", "login-password")\npassword_input.set_meta("gua_sensitive", true)`} /></li></ol>
  <Callout title="No duplicate registration"><p>The adapter recursively collects standard Controls from the root. It observes button signals and routes external click requests back through normal Godot signals.</p></Callout>
  <h2>Commonly observed Controls</h2><div class="grid-2"><div class="mini-card"><strong>Inputs</strong><p>LineEdit, TextEdit, CheckBox, OptionButton, and ItemList</p></div><div class="mini-card"><strong>State</strong><p>Focus, selection, value, scrolling, ranges, visibility, and enabled state</p></div></div>
  <Callout kind="warn" title="Port conflicts"><p>The bridge cannot start if another process already owns port <code>8765</code>. Look for <code>Failed to start Gua Inspector bridge</code> in the Godot output.</p></Callout>
</DocPage>
